[1]
Date: 20 Jan 2005
From: Matias Sacla <matias.sacla@fibertel.com.ar>
Source: Agromeat 14 Jan 2005 [trans. Mod.JGM; edited]
<http://www.agromeat.com/Nota.asp?id=3206>

Uruguay - MGAP confirms 12 cases of equine encephalitis
-------------------
There are now 12 confirmed cases of equine encephalitis with 7 horses dead,
according to figures from the Ministry for Stockbreeding, Agriculture, and
Fishing (MGAP, Ministerio de Ganaderia, Agricultura y Pesca). Deaths were
reported in different slums in Montevideo, and the animals were found by
people picking through garbage.
Mr. Hipolito Tapie, Head of the Sanitation Department in the MGAP, pointed
out that the last case was reported in the El Cerro area. "The last report
of an animal with nervous system symptoms was on 5 Jan 2005 in the El Cerro
area, near Troccoli stadium, and this animal belonged to garbage
pickers. To date, we have registered 12 cases of disease and 7 dead
animals. The sources are Cerrito de la Victoria, Sayago, Malvin Norte,
Pantanoso and El Cerro," he explained.
Everything indicates that the disease is transmitted by mosquitoes and may
prove to be viral encephalitis, even though confirmatory results of the
sera samples sent to the US and Brazil are still awaited. Health
authorities said that if this disease were transmitted to humans, it would
not be lethal; instead, it would resemble flu.
--
Matias Sacla
<matias.sacla@fibertel.com.ar>
